General¶

Your task is to visualize labour / employment data ((https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/daily-quotidien/190308/dq190308a-eng.htm) for Canada by province and industry for the last 5 years which should be pivotable by demographic (age, sex, ethnicity and industry / sector).

Use open skills data and job titles using this link and visualize a mashup correlating skills and jobs to industry and employment and provide a sample for evaluation.

Suggest in detail, how you would train these two data sets over time and what machine learning algorithm you would use to make the data "smarter" over time.

Submission Process:¶

Please begin by creating a Project. Your Project should contain both the final output and a Github link to your source code. Please name all of your files and documents using the following convention: John_Smith_MachineLearning_Nameofyourfile. Once it is completed, you will be able to submit it here to the Work Challenge.

Evaluation Criteria:¶

25% on your approach to tackling the problem and the steps you took to get to your solution and final deliverable 25% on how well you used various tools & processes to tackle the challenge 50% on the final solution and output of your challenge

DataSet Reference:¶

DataSet source:

[1] Province, Gender, Age: Labour force characteristics by province, monthly, seasonally adjusted

[2] Industry: Labour force characteristics by industry, annual

[3] Given DataSet: Job Skills

Task:¶

EDA(Exploratory data analysis) these DataSet, discover valuable infomation and predict some import index

Achievement¶

  1. analyze unemployment rate of gender/age/industry for different province
  2. analyze employment situation of gender/age/industry for different province
  3. analyze popular skills/industry/hiring location
  4. predict umemployment rate based on emplotyment via supervised learning algorithm

For each industry, compare the changes in Employment between this month and the previous month, such as: Accommodation and food services [72] industry, 2015-Dec has increased by 4.5 compared with 2015-November, the growth rate is 0.10074%.

For the convenience of presentation, I selected only the first three industries in Ontario Utilities [22], Agriculture [111-112, 1100, 1151-1152] and Wholesale and retail trade [41, 44-45]

def draw(name):
    sub_df = subIndustry_df[subIndustry_df['Industry']==name]
    x = sub_df['Date']
    y1 = sub_df['Value']
    y2 = sub_df['Value_change_ratio']
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15, 3))
    
    # bar chart
    ax1 = fig.add_subplot(111)
    ax1.bar(x, y1,alpha=.7,color='g')
    ax1.set_ylabel('Value',fontsize='15')
    
    # line chart
    ax2 = ax1.twinx()   # joint chart needed
    ax2.plot(x, y2, 'r',ms=10)
    ax2.set_ylabel('Value change compare last month',fontsize='15')
    # rotation the x labels, look better
    [tick.set_rotation(60) for tick in ax1.get_xticklabels()]
    plt.title('"{}" Employment and changing in Ontario'.format(name), fontsize='20')
    plt.show()

industry_class = subIndustry_df.Industry.value_counts().index
# only show first 3 Industry
for name in industry_class[0:3]:
    draw(name)

Through analysis, we found that in 2017-02, the Wholesale and retail trade industry developed stable, but Agriculture was very sensitive to time changes, which may be related to the season.

Here we have a thought, whether the overall industry development status is related to the unemployment rate? This will be introduced in the machine learning section later.

from wordcloud import WordCloud
import nltk
# first time runn it. you have to download some packages.
# nltk.download('punkt')
# nltk.download('averaged_perceptron_tagger')
# nltk.download('stopwords')
from nltk.corpus import stopwords

text = job_df.Minimum.to_string()
text_list = nltk.word_tokenize(text)
english_punctuations = [',', '.', ':', ';', '?', '(', ')', '[', ']', '&', '!', '*', '@', '#', '$', '%']
text_list = [word for word in text_list if word not in english_punctuations]

stops = set(stopwords.words("english"))
text_list = [word for word in text_list if word not in stops]
text_list = [word for word in text_list if len(word)>5]    # filter words less than 5 char like 'is', 'and', ' with'
text_string = " ".join(text_list)

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 15))
wordcloud = WordCloud(background_color="white",width=1000,height=1000).generate(text_string)
plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation="bilinear")
plt.axis("off")
plt.show()

3 Build mode¶

3.1 Issues we want to solve¶

We know that the unemployment rate is an important indicator that reflects social development. Through previous analysis, how to predict the unemployment rate?

  1. It is related to the development of the industry. With the changes in the employment situation of various industries, the monthly unemployment rate has an impact on it. We can build a model and make a supervised forecast according to the monthly employment situation. The methods used are, for example, we have 70 industries, the corresponding Employment of each industry is Feature, and Prediction is the unemployment rate of the month
  2. Current unemployment rate is related to the previous data, we can establish a time series model and use RNN to predict the unemployment rate
  3. The employment situation of gender and age may also affect the unemployment rate
  4. The employment situation of the industry has an impact on the unemployment rate
  5. The recruitment situation in some industries has a greater impact on the unemployment rate

Based on the above analysis, it was decided to build a model:

  1. Feature has gender, age and employment status in various industries
  2. Predict the Unemployment Rate
  3. Machine learning: RNN and other regressions methods.

3.2.3 Dimensionality Reduction¶

3.3 Select Model¶

In [32]:
from sklearn.linear_model import Ridge
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeRegressor
from sklearn.neural_network import MLPClassifier
from sklearn.svm import SVR

from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
In [33]:
'''
Choose different regressor algorithm, compare the result and choose the best one.
'''
regressor = [
    Ridge(alpha = .3),
    Ridge(alpha = .5),
    Ridge(alpha = .8),
    RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators = 80),
    DecisionTreeRegressor(),
    SVR()
]

cols = ['Regressor', 'MSE']
results = pd.DataFrame(columns=cols)

for reg in regressor:
    reg.fit(X_train, y_train)
    name = reg.__class__.__name__

    print('='*30)
    print(name)
    y_pred = reg.predict(X_test)
    mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
    print('Mean Squared Error: {:.2}\n'.format(mse))

    # Save result
    result_reg = pd.DataFrame([[name, mse]], columns=cols)
    results = results.append(result_reg)

print('*'*30)
